method.description:
A list or llll in the first inlet with buffer names will trigger the slicing; the right portion of buffers is
output from the left outlet, and left portion of buffers is output from the left outlet. 

A number, list or llll in the second inlet sets the split parameter(s): 

in Duration mode: the duration (unit set by timeunit attribute); 

in Number mode: the number of output segments; 

in List mode: the position of split points (unit set by timeunit attribute); 

in Silence mode: amplitude threshold for silence (unit set by ampunit attribute)
and the minimum silence duration (unit set by timeunit attribute); 

in Onset mode: amplitude threshold for attacks (unit set by ampunit attribute)
and the minimum distance between attacks (unit set by timeunit attribute);

Message attributes:

@vbrmode (symbol, default: VBR): VBR mode ("VBR", "CBR" or "ABR")

@bitrate (int): Bitrate in kbps

@minbitrate (int): Minimum bitrate in kbps

@maxbitrate (int): Maximum bitrate in kbps



Save the buffer as lossy compressed MP3 file.
Additional optional arguments specify the buffer index (if more than one buffer are stored in the objct)
and the filename (otherwise a dialog menu will appear).
Additional optional message attributes specify the encoding properties (variable bitrate mode, bitrates). 

Accepted sampletype symbols are : 'int8' (8-bit integer), 'int16' (16-bit integer, default),
'int24' (24-bit integer), 'int32' (32-bit integer), 'float32' (32-bit floating-point),
'float64' (64-bit floating-point), 'mulaw' (8-bit mu-law encoding), 'alaw' (8-bit a-law encoding)

Message attributes:
@correction (int, default: 0): Write correction file along with a lossy wv file
@bitrate (int): Bitrate in kbps
@format (symbol, default: int16): Sample Format
Save the buffer as lossless WavPack compression, or as lossy WavPack compression along with a correction file (if the correction message attribute is set to 1). In this last case, a bitrate message attribute specifies the bitrate of the lossy .wv file in kbps. Additional optional arguments specify the buffer index (if more than one buffer are stored in the objct) and the filename (otherwise a dialog menu will appear). Optional message attributes specify the encoding properties (correction, bitrate, sample ).
Accepted sampletype symbols are : 'int8' (8-bit integer), 'int16' (16-bit integer, default), 'int24' (24-bit integer), 'int32' (32-bit integer), 'float32' (32-bit floating-point), 'float64' (64-bit floating-point), 'mulaw' (8-bit mu-law encoding), 'alaw' (8-bit a-law encoding)

attribute.description:
Sets the blocking mode, i.e. the thread to be used for computation: 

0: the object uses its own separate thread; 

1: the object uses the main thread (default); 

2: the object uses its the scheduler thread. 

The blocking attribute is static: it can only be set in the object box at instantiation.

Sets the split mode: 

0 (Duration): buffer is split into equally long chunks, whose duration is set; 

1 (Number): buffer is split into a fixed number of buffers (such number is set); 

2 (List): buffer is split via a series of split points given as parameter (right inlet); 

3 (Silence): buffer is split according to silence regions. 

4 (Onset): buffer is split according to onset thresholds (set in the right inlet). 

Symbols: "duration", "number", "list" and "silence" can be used while defining the attribute in the object box.

Toggles the ability to output a polybuffer~ instead of a list of buffers: 

- 0 (default) means that no polybuffer is created (individual buffers are output); 

- 1 means that a polybuffer is created and its name is output; 

- 2 means that a polybuffer is created and the individual names of its buffers are output.
